<p class="p">Also calculated is the maximum slope for each centroid. Here slope is estimated as the change in magnitude per unit distance along the path of steepest ascent/descent from a grid point to one of its eight nearest neighbors according to (O'Callaghan &amp; David, 
 <xref rid="wrcr23804-bib-0067" ref-type="ref" class="xref">1984</xref>): 
 <disp-formula id="wrcr23804-disp-0006" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">(6)</label>
  <math id="nlm-math-8" class="math">
   <msub class="msub">
    <mi class="mi">S</mi>
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi class="mi">D</mi>
     <mn class="mn">8</mn>
    </mrow>
   </msub>
   <mo class="mo">=</mo>
   <munder class="munder">
    <mo class="mo">max</mo>
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">gp</mi>
     <mo class="mo">=</mo>
     <mn class="mn">1</mn>
     <mo class="mo">,</mo>
     <mn class="mn">8</mn>
    </mrow>
   </munder>
   <mfrac class="mfrac">
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi class="mi">v</mi>
      <mn class="mn">9</mn>
     </msub>
     <mo class="mo">−</mo>
     <msub class="msub">
      <mi class="mi">v</mi>
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">gp</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mi class="mi">h</mi>
     <mo class="mo">∅</mo>
     <mfenced open="(" close=")" class="mfenced">
      <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">gp</mi>
     </mfenced>
    </mrow>
   </mfrac>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <inline-formula class="inline-formula">∅(
  <italic class="italic">gp</italic>) = 1
 </inline-formula> for 
 <italic class="italic">gp</italic> = 2, 4, 6, and 8 (E, S, N, and W neighbors) and 
 <math id="nlm-math-9" class="math">
  <mo class="mo">∅</mo>
  <mfenced open="(" close=")" class="mfenced">
   <mi mathvariant="italic" class="mi">gp</mi>
  </mfenced>
  <mo class="mo">=</mo>
  <msqrt class="msqrt">
   <mn class="mn">2</mn>
  </msqrt>
 </math> for 
 <italic class="italic">gp</italic> = 1, 2, 5, and 7 (NE, NW, SW, and SE neighbors). This measures the rate of change across the surface in the 
 <italic class="italic">x</italic> and 
 <italic class="italic">y</italic> directions simultaneously and is indicative of overall sensitivity.
</p>
